Student Union Creating Time Capsule
          The Student Union Memorial Center is accepting suggestions for
items to be placed in a time capsule that will be sealed into the new
building during the grand opening in February. Items should capture the
sentiment of our era.
           Ideas can be e-mailed to Chrissy Lieberman, coordinator of campus
activities and Union Galleries, at ceagan@email.arizona.edu , or call
621-8046.

**********
2003 Softball Leadoff Luncheon Jan. 23
          The UA of Intercollegiate Athletics and the Tucson Metropolitan
Chamber of Commerce invite the Tucson community to a 2003 softball season
Leadoff Luncheon.
          The luncheon will be held on Thursday, Jan. 23, at noon at the
Viscount Suite Hotel, 4855 E. Broadway Blvd. Tickets are $25 per seat.
          For information, go to the Arizona Intercollegiate Athletics web
site at http://www.arizonaathletics.com or call the Tucson Metropolitan
Chamber of Commerce at 792-2250 ext. 132.

**********
Career Services to Open in Student Union
           Career Services is closed and will open Monday, Jan. 13, at its
new home on the fourth floor of the Student Union memorial Center, Suite
411.
        Career Services offers students services in selecting majors,
interviewing skills, finding jobs and internships, attending career fairs,
career counseling and other career services.
          To contact Career Services, call 621-4224 or e-mail
careerservices@arizona.edu

**********
Arizona State Museum Celebrates American Indian's Art
          A public reception and opening celebration for "The Art of Luis
David Valenzuela" will be held Saturday, Jan. 11, 4:30 p.m. at the Arizona
State Museum.
          Yaqui artist Louis David Valenzuela, best known for his paintings
of traditional cultural imagery and wooden carved masks, will attend. The
opening celebration includes a performance of Youth Deer Dancers and remarks
by Yaqui language specialist Maria Amarilla. For more information, call
626-8381 or e-mail darlene@al.arizona.edu for more information.

********
Nominations Open for UA Ombuds Committee Members
          Nominations for new members of the Ombuds Committee are being
sought to serve during the 2003-2005 term beginning July 1.
          The UA Ombuds are students, classified staff, appointed personnel,
faculty and administrators who are appointed by the UA president for their
interpersonal skills, their fairness, objectivity and peer respect.
          Ombuds work to promote solutions that are satisfactory to all
parties, and are frequently able to settle conflicts before they reach a
stage where only a grievance system can resolve them.
          Written nominations need to be received in the President¹s Office
by Monday, Feb. 3, or they can be submitted online at
http://w3.arizona.edu/~ombuds/nomination.html . Contact Claudia D¹Albini,
Ombuds Program Coordinator, President¹s Office, 626-5589,
dalbinic@u.arizona.edu <mailto:dalbinic@u.arizona.edu>  for more
information.

********
Faculty-Staff Appreciation Night at Arizona Women's Basketball Jan. 16
          Arizona State Savings and Credit Union and the Arizona Athletics
Department are sponsoring a Faculty/Staff Appreciation Night for the Arizona
Women's Basketball game on Thursday, Jan. 16, at 7 p.m. at McKale Center.
          The 18th-ranked Wildcats will host Pac-10 rival Southern
California. Admission is free for UA faculty and staff and a guest with
CatCard identification.
          Contact Theresa Nassif, at Arizona Athletics, 621-7072 for more
information.

**********
College of Education Staff Raise $1,400 for Shoes for Children
          Seventy children from Sunny View Elementary School in Sunnyside
School District received new shoes in time for Christmas because of the
fund-raising efforts of a group of classified staff employees at the UA
College of Education.
          The college's Staff Advisory Council, a small organization made up
largely of administrative support staff, collected enough money to buy new
shoes for 70 youngsters. Through bake sales, raffles, bottled water sales
and donations, council members met with the children and school
representatives at the Payless shoe store, 740 E. Valencia, on Dec. 9 for a
buying spree.

********
NAU Accepting Proposals for Multicultural And Curriculum Conference
          Proposals for the first multicultural and curriculum conference
that will be held at Northern Arizona University on June 5 and 6 are being
accepted.
          Respecting Diversity in Distance Higher Education: A Multicultural
and Curriculum Conference is being hosted by NAU's TECH Share Project at the
Institute for Future Work Force Development, Faculty Development, and the
Center for Teaching and Enhanced Learning.
          Individuals in administrative services, information resources,
K-12 or University level teaching and learning, technology infrastructure,
faculty development or management within distance higher education are
encouraged to attend.
          Go to the conference website, http://www4.nau.edu/ifwfd/diversity/
for information to submit a presentation or interactive poster proposal or
register for the conference. Deadline to submit a proposal is Saturday, Feb.
15.
        For more information, contact Linda Neff, Institute for Future Work
Force Development at NAU at (928) 523-1761 or 1 (800) 522-2283.

************
Flandrau Offers Free Admission to All CatCard Holders
          The Flandrau Science Center beginning Jan. 15 is offering free
admission to its exhibit halls and regularly scheduled planetarium shows to
all current CatCard holders. This includes all UA faculty, staff and
students.
          CatCard holders also are eligible to sign up for discounts in the
Flandrau's June Patterson Science Store.
          The center is re-opening on Mondays and will now be open seven
days a week: Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., Thursday,
Friday, and Saturday from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. and 7 to 9 p.m., and Sunday from
1 to 5 p.m.
          Read more at UA News Services at http://uanews.org under the Lo
Que Pasa heading.

**********
Campus Rec Offers 2 Weeks Free
          Faculty and staff are invited to enjoy for free the Department of
Campus Recreation's facilities for two weeks, Jan. 11-21.
          Faculty and staff just need to bring their CatCard for free use of
any of the department's facilities including the Student Recreation Center,
the Bear Down Gym/Bear Down Weight Room and the Robson Tennis Center.
          Individuals who sign up for a new annual membership during this
period will receive a free 10-week Faculty-Staff Fitness Pass.
          For more information, contact Jody at 621-8715, e-mail
jliller@e-mail.arizona.edu or go to the Campus Recreation Department
website, http://campusrec.arizona.edu/hours/

**********
UA to Host Reception for Outgoing Extended U Dean
          Vice President for Undergraduate Education Randall M. Richardson
invites the University community to a farewell reception for Anita McDonald
on Thursday, Jan. 30, from 3 - 5 p.m. at the Marriott Hotel University Park.
          McDonald, dean of Extended University, has accepted the position
of chief executive officer of the DuBois Campus of Pennsylvania State
University
          McDonald has played a crucial role in Extended University,
enhancing the quality of education for UA students and the community. Her
skills, knowledge, and community awareness will be sorely missed, as will
her numerous contributions to Extended University and the Tucson community
as a whole, said Richardson in a statement distributed University-wide.

**********
Three Distant Quasars Found at Edge of the Universe
          Astronomers with the Sloan Digital Sky Survey have discovered
three of the oldest, most distant quasars yet found -- quasars close to the
Big Bang that began the universe.
          Xiaohui Fan of the UA Steward Observatory presented the results at
the American Astronomical Society's meeting in Seattle in Jan. 9.
          Read more at the UA News Services web site under the Science
heading at http://uanews.org

**********
UA Engineering Alum to Walk in Space Jan. 15
          UA engineering alum Don Pettit is scheduled to take a spacewalk
outside the International Space Station (ISS) on Wednesday, Jan. 15. Pettit
and Expedition Six Commander Ken Bowersox will spend more than six hours
working outside the space station.
          Coverage of the spacewalk will begin on NASA TV at 6 a.m. EST,
with the spacewalk scheduled to begin around 7 a.m. EST.
          Read more at the UA News Services web site under the Engineering &
Mines heading at http://uanews.org

**********
New Thinking About Government and Taxes Needed
          Marshall Vest, director of the Economic and Business Research
Program at the UA, dissects some myths about taxes, the role of government
and just how tax policy affects this state's economy.
          Read more at the UA News Services web site under the Business
heading at http://uanews.org

**********
Women's Mental Health Symposium, Jan. 25
          The UA College of Medicine will present a symposium that will
address current mental health care issues specific to women, including an
overview of women's mood disorders, chronic depression, stress management,
postpartum depression, domestic violence, fibromyalgia, Alzheimer's disease,
anxiety disorders, hormone replacement and more.
          An award, "Hero in Women's Mental Health," will be presented to a
person who has displayed pioneering efforts and had a positive impact in
women's mental health.
          The event is open to all specialties of health care providers.
          Read more at the UA News Services web site under the Health
heading at http://uanews.org

